which read David Wallace Wells' book.

20:02.880 --> 20:05.680
If you haven't, there are grim fates in store

20:05.680 --> 20:09.040
for us in every country,

20:09.040 --> 20:11.480
if we let temperature rise more than that.

20:11.480 --> 20:13.280
So we've got to act quickly.

20:13.280 --> 20:16.680
And I think the investments we need to make,

20:16.680 --> 20:18.880
many can come in the private sector.

20:18.880 --> 20:22.920
We can guide them as we have in the past

20:22.920 --> 20:27.920
with subsidies for renewable energy investments and the like.

20:27.920 --> 20:32.920
There is now a very exciting new technology

20:33.880 --> 20:38.880
developed by ClimbWorks in Switzerland

20:39.240 --> 20:41.000
to suck carbon out of the air

20:41.000 --> 20:43.680
and turn it into a carbon-based slurry

20:43.680 --> 20:45.160
that you pump deep underground.

20:45.160 --> 20:47.240
And it's very expensive now,

20:47.240 --> 20:51.360
but we're on a track to have the cost of that come down

20:51.360 --> 20:54.320
rapidly enough to where it too could make a difference.

20:54.320 --> 20:57.880
But all this is going to require an enormous amount of money.

20:57.880 --> 21:00.880
We've got an enormous amount of money.

21:00.880 --> 21:03.440
That's not the problem.

21:03.440 --> 21:07.040
The problem is to persuade people to part

21:07.040 --> 21:09.960
with what they're using the money for now

21:09.960 --> 21:12.720
and to use it instead for these other things,

21:12.720 --> 21:14.600
that if we don't use it for them,

21:14.600 --> 21:16.600
there's not going to be a future for us.

21:16.600 --> 21:20.160
And so I think that means if you want to be practical,

21:20.160 --> 21:22.800
looking to the top of the income pyramid,

21:22.800 --> 21:25.840
there's enormous resources there.

21:25.840 --> 21:28.480
We've been hearing about wealth taxes

21:28.480 --> 21:31.640
and how small the bite they need to take

21:31.640 --> 21:35.120
in order to generate enormous pools of resources

21:35.120 --> 21:39.800
to invest in these public projects that need to happen.

21:39.800 --> 21:43.560
I'm not worried about people lacking incentives

21:43.560 --> 21:47.760
to grow wealthy if they have to pay a little bit more in tax.

21:47.760 --> 21:51.080
There's a huge literature on the determinants

21:51.080 --> 21:52.480
of human flourishing.

21:52.480 --> 21:54.760
It's contentious.

21:54.760 --> 21:57.120
People argue about many of the findings in it.

21:57.120 --> 21:59.240
The one thing they don't argue about,

21:59.240 --> 22:03.400
the one really secure finding that's held up in every study

22:03.400 --> 22:05.360
is that beyond a certain point,

22:05.360 --> 22:07.240
and it's one we've long since passed,

22:07.240 --> 22:09.800
and most countries in the West have too,

22:09.800 --> 22:13.280
further increases in consumption

22:13.280 --> 22:17.280
serve only to raise the bar that we think of as adequate.

22:17.280 --> 22:20.800
So if all the mansions get 10% bigger,

22:20.800 --> 22:24.000
the people living in them aren't any happier,

22:24.000 --> 22:26.760
any healthier than they were before.

22:26.760 --> 22:31.760
If the cars get bigger, people aren't only not happier.

22:31.960 --> 22:34.600
They're at more risk of death and injury.

22:34.600 --> 22:36.880
We burn up more fossil fuels.

22:36.880 --> 22:39.320
All of these things could be changed

22:39.320 --> 22:41.640
if we changed people's incentives,

22:41.640 --> 22:44.720
and we've got simple tax levers that can do that.

22:44.720 --> 22:47.280
So yes, incentives are important,

22:47.280 --> 22:51.880
and we've been steering people with the wrong incentives.

22:51.880 --> 22:54.520
Thus far, that's why we're in the best that we're in.

22:58.880 --> 23:01.320
I guess I should jump in to just ask,

23:01.320 --> 23:04.960
you know, a kind of meta question about economics

23:04.960 --> 23:06.080
or the field of economics,

23:06.080 --> 23:08.160
which is something I grapple with,

23:08.160 --> 23:10.680
is how much is the field of economics itself

23:10.680 --> 23:15.480
responsible for those misaligned incentives?

23:15.480 --> 23:19.320
And so I'm one of the people here who did major in economics

23:19.320 --> 23:22.000
as an undergrad, then a master's in economics,

23:22.000 --> 23:26.000
and realized I did not want to get a PhD in economics.

23:26.880 --> 23:31.120
I know Rich, you and Bob have survived the field,

23:31.120 --> 23:33.240
and I'm sort of curious, you know,

23:33.240 --> 23:35.680
when Nicholas says like, what really works?

23:35.680 --> 23:40.280
How much should we look to economists for what really works?

23:40.280 --> 23:42.520
I feel like we've been gravely misled

23:42.520 --> 23:46.280
by some of the assumptions and ideologies of the field.

23:46.280 --> 23:50.160
And also some serious levers for human behavior

23:50.160 --> 23:53.480
have been overlooked, including reputation, of course,

23:53.480 --> 23:56.320
and reputation being the primary mechanism

23:56.320 --> 23:58.760
to enforce the Paris Agreement.

23:58.760 --> 24:00.800
And it's something economists don't,

24:00.800 --> 24:02.800
I think, address very well.

24:03.800 --> 24:06.160
And I've been very disturbed more recently

24:06.160 --> 24:07.760
by the fact that, you know,

24:07.760 --> 24:10.880
the student divestment movement around fossil fuels,

24:10.880 --> 24:14.080
the pushback within academia has come primarily

24:14.080 --> 24:16.640
from economics professors.

24:16.640 --> 24:20.520
And this strikes me again as an area of tension

24:20.520 --> 24:22.640
where we have this kind of hubris

24:22.640 --> 24:27.640
about what really works in an era of mass unpredictability

24:29.440 --> 24:31.720
and a kind of lack of humility, I would say,

24:31.720 --> 24:34.800
on the part of economists in general,

24:34.800 --> 24:38.720
not, of course, specifically to anyone in this roundtable,

24:38.720 --> 24:42.840
but about, you know, asking what really works.

24:42.840 --> 24:46.080
When psychologists start winning the Nobel Prize in economics,

24:46.080 --> 24:47.800
you should start doubting, you know,

24:47.800 --> 24:50.380
the tenets of your discipline.

24:51.480 --> 24:53.480
Well, I think that's the thing.

24:53.480 --> 24:55.720
I mean, if we're going to be serious about it,

24:55.720 --> 24:58.600
you cannot attack a field of study.

24:58.600 --> 25:02.040
I mean, seriously, I mean, that would be just dumb.

25:02.040 --> 25:04.640
I mean, there is diversity among people.

25:04.640 --> 25:08.880
People have right used the same quantitative tools

25:08.880 --> 25:10.320
with different assumptions

25:10.320 --> 25:11.960
and they're all different conclusions.

25:11.960 --> 25:14.520
Not the way I see economics.

25:14.520 --> 25:17.600
Like people would do that in physics

25:17.600 --> 25:19.920
or in psychology or in other fields.

25:19.920 --> 25:24.160
It's a science, you know, not everybody agrees.

25:25.120 --> 25:28.600
But I think practically everybody agrees

25:28.600 --> 25:30.960
that incentives work.

25:30.960 --> 25:33.920
And I think that Robert's ideas

25:33.920 --> 25:36.600
about how to change incentives are, in my opinion,

25:36.600 --> 25:37.880
very important.

25:37.880 --> 25:41.440
And society as a whole has to think seriously

25:41.440 --> 25:44.040
what possibilities there are there.

25:44.040 --> 25:49.040
I think there is a conflict between trying to take away

25:51.720 --> 25:54.160
the wealth of whoever is the wealth individual,

25:54.160 --> 25:57.080
or whatever that is,

25:57.080 --> 26:00.600
and trying to create the right incentives

26:00.600 --> 26:04.120
even for the objectives that you were talking about

26:04.120 --> 26:06.120
of green growth, for example.

26:06.120 --> 26:09.120
I mean, there could be a lot of different ways

26:09.120 --> 26:12.280
to achieve that green growth without screwing up

26:12.280 --> 26:15.040
the incentives of the society for investment.

26:15.040 --> 26:17.120
Because after all, you know,

26:17.120 --> 26:19.160
when we're talking about wealth individuals

26:19.160 --> 26:21.960
with multi-billion dollar wealth,

26:21.960 --> 26:24.800
when we take away, let's say a billion dollars

26:24.800 --> 26:26.760
or 10 billion dollars from them,

26:26.760 --> 26:28.720
we're not changing consumption

26:28.720 --> 26:32.120
because these people cannot possibly consume

26:32.120 --> 26:33.440
that amount of money.

26:33.440 --> 26:35.720
We're taking it away from investment.

26:35.720 --> 26:38.720
So that would have to be, you know, truthful about it.

26:38.720 --> 26:40.320
We're taking it away from investment.

26:40.320 --> 26:43.080
So the real question is,

26:43.080 --> 26:46.680
is the government good in doing investments?

26:46.680 --> 26:49.120
And everybody knows that it's not true.

26:49.120 --> 26:50.480
It's not true.

26:50.480 --> 26:53.160
The government, if you give it 10 billion dollars,

26:53.160 --> 26:56.000
it's going to be wasted to a very large extent.

26:56.000 --> 26:58.800
And we all agree on that.

26:58.800 --> 27:03.360
So we have to think of ways in which the incentives

27:03.360 --> 27:07.760
are set up so that the private sector produces

27:07.760 --> 27:11.640
what we want, the green growth that we all agree we want.

27:11.640 --> 27:13.440
So we need to think of that.

27:13.440 --> 27:14.880
And this is a serious issue.

27:14.880 --> 27:16.360
I mean, it's not trivial.

27:16.360 --> 27:19.240
And we need to work on it.

27:19.240 --> 27:20.680
I mean, how can I put it?

27:20.680 --> 27:22.760
I mean, just general declarations,

27:22.760 --> 27:26.480
let's take the portal that Bezos has.

27:26.480 --> 27:29.080
I mean, that doesn't, we'll not get us anywhere.

27:29.080 --> 27:31.440
We need to think of incentives

27:31.440 --> 27:35.680
for the private sector to invest in this areas

27:35.680 --> 27:37.240
that we're interested to invest.

27:37.240 --> 27:38.480
Thank you.

27:38.480 --> 27:42.880
And luxury fever, in 1990, I came out

27:42.880 --> 27:45.840
and you had the graduated conception tax.

27:45.840 --> 27:48.640
And that's a really good idea, because we live in a society

27:48.640 --> 27:50.880
that is Galbraith said back in the 50s,

27:50.880 --> 27:53.400
is characterized by what?

27:53.400 --> 27:56.320
Private splendor and public squalor.

27:56.320 --> 28:01.080
And we're arguably, because of status externalities

28:01.080 --> 28:05.680
and positional goods, we've constructed a society

28:05.680 --> 28:08.600
where we have excessive levels of private consumption

28:08.600 --> 28:11.280
and we under invest in public goods

28:11.280 --> 28:12.960
and in public infrastructure.

28:12.960 --> 28:14.960
And I think I agree with Robert Frank

28:14.960 --> 28:17.440
that most of, or many of the investments that now

28:17.440 --> 28:21.640
are most important, the public sector has to be in the lead

28:21.640 --> 28:24.600
on that and it has to be done at a global level.

28:24.600 --> 28:26.880
And so what works, I think, is something

28:26.880 --> 28:29.960
that looks more like social democracy

28:29.960 --> 28:34.880
than like laissez-fieck fear of capitalism.

28:34.880 --> 28:37.440
Now, maybe we need to look back at what works

28:37.440 --> 28:41.240
in the New Deal era in the 50s and 60s.

28:41.240 --> 28:44.240
There are some problems there, but maybe we need to go back

28:44.240 --> 28:46.680
towards a better balance between the public

28:46.680 --> 28:47.680
and private sector.

28:47.680 --> 28:49.160
And it should be incentive-based

28:49.160 --> 28:51.400
and it should be investment-focused.

28:52.880 --> 28:56.320
Nick, you said we all agree that when government

28:56.320 --> 28:58.320
invests they do a bad job of it,

28:58.320 --> 29:00.160
I don't think we all agree about that,

29:00.160 --> 29:02.600
at least I don't agree with it.

29:02.600 --> 29:04.680
They do a bad job in some cases,

29:04.680 --> 29:08.040
but in other cases there are investments

29:08.040 --> 29:11.240
that the private sector simply doesn't have any incentive

29:11.240 --> 29:14.640
to make so that even if the government did a poor job

29:14.640 --> 29:17.480
with them it would be better than not seeing them happen

29:17.480 --> 29:19.480
at all, but there are plenty of examples

29:19.480 --> 29:22.160
where the government's done a splendidly good job

29:22.160 --> 29:23.360
with public investment.

29:23.360 --> 29:26.520
I mean, there are massive public works,

29:26.520 --> 29:28.840
product programs all over the world

29:28.840 --> 29:31.320
that do an enormous amount of good for the citizens

29:31.320 --> 29:32.800
of their countries.

29:32.800 --> 29:36.120
Why do we insist that the government's not pretty good

29:36.120 --> 29:37.360
at things like that?

29:39.920 --> 29:44.600
If I may, I mean, I would say the reason why the government

29:44.600 --> 29:47.800
might not be as good as you think on that

29:47.800 --> 29:51.800
is because the government is run by politicians

29:51.800 --> 29:54.240
and politicians need to be reelected.

29:54.240 --> 29:57.400
So on top of their minds is how they're going to please

29:57.400 --> 29:59.760
the public and to get the real act.

29:59.760 --> 30:02.760
And one way to please the public is to take this money

30:02.760 --> 30:06.560
that they have under their control and double it down,

30:06.560 --> 30:09.720
give it to the public rather than invest it,

30:09.720 --> 30:12.520
even though you're absolutely right, Robert,

30:12.520 --> 30:16.920
that investing it in some public goods

30:16.920 --> 30:20.480
is in fact an excellent idea.

30:20.480 --> 30:25.160
There are of course aspects of the economy

30:25.160 --> 30:28.360
where the incentives for the private sector are not big enough.

30:28.360 --> 30:30.320
I mean, that's for sure.

30:30.320 --> 30:33.440
But the problem is that there is a conflict

30:33.440 --> 30:38.560
at the government level because we are human beings.

30:38.560 --> 30:41.560
We're run by politicians whose top priority

30:41.560 --> 30:44.600
is to get reelected and there's no doubt about that.

30:44.600 --> 30:47.560
The top priority is not to make the United States great.

30:47.560 --> 30:50.160
The top priority is to get reelected.

30:50.160 --> 30:53.520
And to do that, they're going to distribute the money

30:53.520 --> 30:55.600
to the voters.

30:55.600 --> 30:59.320
And that's in that problem is going to be there,

30:59.320 --> 31:01.520
no matter what government we have,

31:01.520 --> 31:03.720
as long as we have an elected government,

31:03.720 --> 31:05.000
it's going to be there.

31:05.000 --> 31:08.360
And therefore we need to take it into account and say,

31:08.360 --> 31:13.360
well, do we really want to give huge amounts of money

31:14.720 --> 31:17.000
from the private sector to the public sector?

31:17.000 --> 31:19.280
Or we know it has less productivity.

31:19.280 --> 31:21.120
Are we, do we need to do that?

31:21.120 --> 31:22.960
Except for a very essential stuff,

31:22.960 --> 31:25.400
like national defense, for example,

31:25.400 --> 31:29.200
in which we don't want to give it to the private sector.

31:29.200 --> 31:32.680
So it's important to think about it

31:32.680 --> 31:36.280
and not jump to conclusions and say,

31:36.280 --> 31:37.200
oh yeah, great.

31:37.200 --> 31:40.240
I mean, that just because the government

31:40.240 --> 31:42.920
is doing some good job in some investments,

31:42.920 --> 31:45.240
let's give them a huge project,

31:45.240 --> 31:47.840
which is the green project to them.

31:47.840 --> 31:51.280
But rather try to find ways to do it in the private sector.

31:52.440 --> 31:54.240
I just like to.

31:54.240 --> 31:55.880
I would challenge that, Nicholas,

31:55.880 --> 31:59.400
because that analysis,

31:59.400 --> 32:02.680
because how do politicians get elected?

32:04.440 --> 32:08.000
Undiably, we now have less of a democracy

32:08.000 --> 32:11.000
and more of a plutocracy.

32:11.000 --> 32:15.280
And knowing the amount of money

32:15.280 --> 32:18.760
from the big corporate sector

32:18.760 --> 32:22.200
that goes into campaign funds.

32:22.200 --> 32:26.040
So that has distorted our democracy.

32:26.040 --> 32:28.160
And many people have pointed that out.

32:28.160 --> 32:32.880
So therefore, the politicians that are elected

32:32.880 --> 32:34.840
tend to serve the interests

32:34.840 --> 32:37.960
of their big campaign contributors.

32:37.960 --> 32:40.160
This is not rocket science.

32:40.160 --> 32:44.360
I would add in terms of what I would call

32:44.360 --> 32:48.480
trickle down economics or neoliberal economics,

32:48.480 --> 32:52.040
which basically that's what I'm hearing from you.

32:52.040 --> 32:54.360
With all respect, I am.

32:54.360 --> 32:59.360
And let me give a case study from my community in D.C.

33:01.160 --> 33:04.880
We have an elected city, a local government.

33:04.880 --> 33:08.880
Of course, we don't have statehood.

33:08.880 --> 33:10.640
We're fighting for it.

33:10.640 --> 33:13.800
And actually, the big prime instrument

33:13.800 --> 33:16.880
of fossil capital, Senator Manchin,

33:16.880 --> 33:20.120
is blocking that among a few others

33:20.120 --> 33:22.840
to actually have self-determination.

33:22.840 --> 33:27.160
But our own economic policies and social policies

33:27.160 --> 33:32.200
in our D.C. have been dominated by trickle down economics.

33:32.200 --> 33:34.800
And what has this resulted in?

33:34.800 --> 33:39.280
D.C. now has the biggest life expectancy gap

33:39.280 --> 33:42.800
in the country compared to 50 states

33:42.800 --> 33:45.680
between black and white residents.

33:45.680 --> 33:49.920
It actually has grown in the last 20 years.

33:49.920 --> 33:52.600
It's shockingly high.

33:52.600 --> 33:56.400
And this is a reflection of where the priorities

33:56.400 --> 34:01.400
of public spending and the fact that our politicians

34:02.160 --> 34:05.240
that are in power in our local government

34:05.240 --> 34:09.680
are basically beholden to the big developer class,

34:09.680 --> 34:11.680
which has gentrified D.C.,

34:11.680 --> 34:16.680
which has forced residents out, long-term residents.

34:16.680 --> 34:21.680
And so I'm going by our own experience in our local government,

34:21.800 --> 34:26.800
our local community in terms of the impacts of these policies.

34:27.880 --> 34:30.920
And we also have seen in the pandemic

34:30.920 --> 34:35.840
how the billionaire class has grown even richer

34:36.760 --> 34:40.400
and income inequality has grown.

34:40.400 --> 34:43.720
And finally, what does that mean to health?

34:43.720 --> 34:48.720
If we look at the life expectancy of in the United States,

34:50.120 --> 34:54.720
compared to its cohort of wealthy countries,

34:54.720 --> 34:57.560
we're ranked about 40 in the world.

34:57.560 --> 34:59.560
A matter of fact, Cuba and the US

34:59.560 --> 35:02.160
have about the same life expectancy now.

35:03.200 --> 35:06.200
I wonder if I, I think, I'm sorry, David,

35:06.200 --> 35:10.160
so Jennifer, you also had something to add at that point.

35:10.160 --> 35:12.560
I'm gonna mute.

35:12.560 --> 35:17.560
I would just say that, of course, you can attack an entire field.

35:17.800 --> 35:19.520
I mean, we have many times in the past,

35:19.520 --> 35:21.760
we attacked the field of eugenics right now,

35:21.760 --> 35:24.000
critical race theory is under attack.

35:24.000 --> 35:27.600
You can most certainly attack a whole field.

35:28.480 --> 35:31.320
And I think it's worth questioning,

35:31.320 --> 35:33.200
especially with the premise of this roundtable

35:33.200 --> 35:37.680
was about the sort of role of the dismal science of economics,

35:37.680 --> 35:40.160
which is not, of course, in fact, a science.

35:40.160 --> 35:44.320
Economics uses scientific tools, it uses empiricism.

35:44.320 --> 35:47.560
But if you know anything about the epistemology of science,

35:47.560 --> 35:51.080
terms like good and necessary growth

35:51.080 --> 35:55.120
or trickle down economics, these are all normative assumptions.

35:55.120 --> 35:57.360
They're all values that we bring,

35:57.360 --> 35:58.920
rich I see you nodding, I'm sure,

35:58.920 --> 36:02.840
ecological economics has these kind of arguments all the time

36:02.840 --> 36:07.360
about the values that are baked into the research.

36:07.360 --> 36:10.920
And so I think what I'm interested in

36:10.920 --> 36:14.760
is the way in which, especially members of this panel

36:14.760 --> 36:17.400
have grappled with some of those assumptions

36:17.400 --> 36:21.480
in the field of economics and are trying to modernize

36:21.480 --> 36:25.400
or make them relevant to the 21st century,

36:25.400 --> 36:30.400
make them less glaringly insufficient

36:30.600 --> 36:33.880
as they were, I think, in the 20th.

36:33.880 --> 36:35.960
I mean, that's a good question.

36:35.960 --> 36:38.840
I mean, I also say that the government,

36:38.840 --> 36:40.960
democracy isn't working well in America.

36:40.960 --> 36:43.560
What is working well is the ability of corporations

36:43.560 --> 36:48.120
to get all a distance left that who pursue corporate interests.

36:48.120 --> 36:50.280
And so we've been through 30 or 40 years of that.

36:50.280 --> 36:54.200
We have an economy now that is built around rent capture

36:54.200 --> 36:55.400
and rent seeking.

