55:27.360 --> 55:30.920
And they've gotten hundreds of millions of dollars

55:30.920 --> 55:35.920
in back taxes through a threat of a disincentive, which

55:35.920 --> 55:38.520
is to just expose your name.

55:38.520 --> 55:43.720
It's just reputation, and it costs very little.

55:43.720 --> 55:46.680
And you ask, well, why disincentives?

55:46.680 --> 55:48.160
What happened to the incentive?

55:48.160 --> 55:51.600
Well, what we're going to honor people who pay their taxes?

55:51.600 --> 55:54.600
It all depends on the norm, right?

55:54.600 --> 55:58.360
We're going to honor people who write the best album of the year

55:58.360 --> 56:00.520
or make the best movie of the year.

56:00.520 --> 56:05.520
But when you're dealing with delinquent taxpayers,

56:05.520 --> 56:08.760
disincentives are really the only option in the system.

56:08.760 --> 56:14.280
There is not an incentive mirror in that kind of social problem.

56:14.280 --> 56:16.320
The thing is that no one's given Nicholas an opportunity

56:16.320 --> 56:20.200
to express how there might be a positive incentive.

56:20.200 --> 56:23.240
In this scenario of providing equity to workers,

56:23.240 --> 56:27.160
I just wonder what you thought about that.

56:27.160 --> 56:27.880
Sure.

56:27.880 --> 56:32.320
I mean, the standard, the way in which the government provides

56:32.320 --> 56:35.640
incentives is through taxation.

56:35.640 --> 56:39.520
So if you did, for example, it went to Amazon and said,

56:39.520 --> 56:41.640
well, we'll tax you a bit less.

56:41.640 --> 56:44.240
Or for this particular shares that you're

56:44.240 --> 56:48.280
going to transfer to workers or potentially transfer to workers,

56:48.280 --> 56:53.400
offer them to workers besides their regular compensation.

56:53.400 --> 56:54.800
That could work, right?

56:54.800 --> 56:58.880
I mean, that could create an incentive for any corporation

56:58.880 --> 57:03.120
to say, now from now on, from 2022,

57:03.120 --> 57:07.120
we're going to hire people and not just pay them $20 an hour,

57:07.120 --> 57:10.120
but we're going to also give them some percentage

57:10.120 --> 57:13.040
of the corporation so that we'll have in the future

57:13.040 --> 57:14.800
some percentage of the profits.

57:14.800 --> 57:17.560
You can even give it in a different way

57:17.560 --> 57:19.360
in which you can loan them the shares

57:19.360 --> 57:21.160
so they can get some percentage of the profits.

57:21.160 --> 57:23.080
There are ways to do these things,

57:23.080 --> 57:25.280
but they're not clobbering the rich.

57:25.280 --> 57:31.160
This is a way to figure out a way so that self-driven interest

57:31.160 --> 57:33.520
of these guys who manage these companies

57:33.520 --> 57:38.480
would create a more just society in the future

57:38.480 --> 57:41.320
and through using positive incentives.

57:41.320 --> 57:42.520
I think that's important.

57:42.520 --> 57:46.160
I think that's a way in my experience in life, maybe not

57:46.160 --> 57:47.800
yours, but in my experience in life,

57:47.800 --> 57:52.040
people respond much more positively, much more easily

57:52.040 --> 57:53.960
and positive to positive incentives

57:53.960 --> 57:56.800
than negative incentives.

57:56.800 --> 57:58.040
Let me just jump in one more time.

57:58.040 --> 58:00.560
I wondered though, Nicholas, if you think

58:00.560 --> 58:04.640
that clobbering the rich isn't a good idea

58:04.640 --> 58:07.720
because it's too severe of punishment

58:07.720 --> 58:10.080
or it's too negative for them to tolerate

58:10.080 --> 58:14.880
or whether it just provides the public

58:14.880 --> 58:20.160
with a negative view of capital.

58:20.160 --> 58:23.080
Well, I mean, I won't go into the sociology kind of issue.

58:23.080 --> 58:30.320
So why this thing might be bad for psychologically or socially?

58:30.320 --> 58:34.720
But I want to say it from only purely economic point of view,

58:34.720 --> 58:38.080
if you take $20 billion away from Bezos,

58:38.080 --> 58:41.800
you are not taking it away from his consumption, right?

58:41.800 --> 58:44.960
You're not restricting them from buying a great house

58:44.960 --> 58:48.080
or a great yacht or whatever.

58:48.080 --> 58:51.760
You are taking it away from investment, OK?

58:51.760 --> 58:53.480
That money was going to investment,

58:53.480 --> 58:56.120
and now it's going to the government.

58:56.120 --> 58:59.280
And we will see if the government actually invested

58:59.280 --> 59:03.280
or let's say invest 30% of it and give the way

59:03.280 --> 59:06.640
to the voters, the remaining part.

59:06.640 --> 59:10.640
So that's important because that says

59:10.640 --> 59:16.520
that we are changing the investment

59:16.520 --> 59:18.880
to consumption ratio in the country.

59:18.880 --> 59:20.840
And we need investment.

59:20.840 --> 59:25.120
That's why I said you should be careful about taking away

59:25.120 --> 59:28.880
this money because the way politicians have presented it,

59:28.880 --> 59:31.440
it's as if it's just free.

59:31.440 --> 59:34.040
There is no bad consequences of it.

59:34.040 --> 59:37.440
How can it be bad to take $20 billion from Bezos?

59:37.440 --> 59:40.000
And I have nothing to do with Bezos and Amazon, by the way.

59:40.000 --> 59:42.920
Just I'm not an anyway concerned.

59:42.920 --> 59:44.800
But how can it be bad?

59:44.800 --> 59:46.600
People don't even think about it,

59:46.600 --> 59:49.960
but it has significant negative consequences,

59:49.960 --> 59:51.320
at least in my opinion.

59:51.320 --> 59:54.400
So we can think of other ways in which we can,

59:54.400 --> 59:57.880
if we need money to finance ourselves,

59:57.880 --> 01:00:00.480
I mean, when we can create more investment,

01:00:00.480 --> 01:00:01.880
we can think about it.

01:00:01.880 --> 01:00:04.360
In my opinion, it would make more sense

01:00:04.360 --> 01:00:06.280
to give money to the private sector

01:00:06.280 --> 01:00:08.920
to do investments rather than the public sector

01:00:08.920 --> 01:00:11.680
because traditionally the public sector

01:00:11.680 --> 01:00:17.120
doesn't reduce as good results as the private sector.

01:00:17.120 --> 01:00:18.720
And I think that is, in general,

01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:20.680
we've understood in the United States.

01:00:20.680 --> 01:00:23.640
I mean, we don't try, we don't see the United States

01:00:23.640 --> 01:00:25.920
try to make its own fighter planes.

01:00:25.920 --> 01:00:29.080
They don't, they just try to give the contracts

01:00:29.080 --> 01:00:33.480
to the private sector and in many, many, many other dimensions.

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:36.800
So, I don't know, in other countries,

01:00:36.800 --> 01:00:39.120
it's possible in Cuba, things happen differently.

01:00:39.120 --> 01:00:42.880
It's possible in China, things happen differently.

01:00:42.880 --> 01:00:45.040
It's possible in Russia, things happen differently,

01:00:45.040 --> 01:00:46.480
but not in the United States.

01:00:46.480 --> 01:00:49.240
So, given the environment we live in,

01:00:49.240 --> 01:00:53.080
we should think of ways to tweak it in the right direction

01:00:54.440 --> 01:00:56.200
rather than in the wrong direction.

01:00:56.200 --> 01:00:58.840
I mean, my students are usually shocked

01:00:58.840 --> 01:01:00.760
when I tell them that in the 1970s,

01:01:00.760 --> 01:01:03.560
the top marginal tax rate was 70%.

01:01:03.560 --> 01:01:05.560
And somehow that didn't prevent the economy

01:01:05.560 --> 01:01:08.640
from being productive and inefficient.

01:01:08.640 --> 01:01:10.400
And it didn't forestall abroad.

01:01:10.400 --> 01:01:12.000
And I looked at Build Back Better,

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:15.440
which is now stalled in the Senate.

01:01:15.440 --> 01:01:19.040
And Build Back Better isn't about massive tax increases.

01:01:19.040 --> 01:01:20.440
It's about spending what?

01:01:20.440 --> 01:01:23.680
Maybe one or two percent of national income

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:27.160
to address some critical problems relating to education

01:01:27.160 --> 01:01:30.400
and social justice and also decarbonization.

01:01:30.400 --> 01:01:34.360
And markets aren't going to get that those jobs done

01:01:34.360 --> 01:01:35.760
are working on their own.

01:01:35.760 --> 01:01:38.640
Market failures have caused those problems.

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:40.960
And a male distribution of wealth

01:01:40.960 --> 01:01:43.880
has contributed to those problems, including.

01:01:43.880 --> 01:01:47.120
So I look at public schools and I'm very concerned

01:01:47.120 --> 01:01:49.480
about the inequality that we see in education

01:01:49.480 --> 01:01:53.000
between people in privileged communities

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:56.160
like the town that I live in and I'm an amateur.

01:01:56.160 --> 01:01:59.000
And then I look at poor black and brown communities

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:00.560
because they don't have good schools

01:02:00.560 --> 01:02:02.440
and they don't have good public services.

01:02:02.440 --> 01:02:04.320
And we need to invest in those people,

01:02:04.320 --> 01:02:06.880
not just for the sake of us communities,

01:02:06.880 --> 01:02:08.840
not just for the sake of social justice,

01:02:08.840 --> 01:02:11.040
but also because that's human capital

01:02:11.040 --> 01:02:14.160
and that's where our nation's future lies.

01:02:16.240 --> 01:02:21.240
Richard, you could mention also that in Build Back Better,

01:02:22.160 --> 01:02:27.160
the final version that was blocked by two senators.

01:02:28.880 --> 01:02:33.880
It also, what they gutted out provision to tax rich

01:02:34.600 --> 01:02:39.600
because of a few Wall Street inclined Democrats

01:02:39.600 --> 01:02:41.560
that got that removed.

01:02:41.560 --> 01:02:44.800
And not only, remember under Eisenhower,

01:02:44.800 --> 01:02:48.280
the top marginal rate was over 90%.

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:49.200
That's true.

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:50.040
Yeah.

01:02:50.040 --> 01:02:52.440
And matter of fact, the latest issue of the nation

01:02:52.440 --> 01:02:56.680
has a proposal to bring that marginal rate back.

01:02:56.680 --> 01:02:59.680
Nevertheless, even with that marginal rate,

01:02:59.680 --> 01:03:02.640
and I've looked into tax issues in DC,

01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:05.760
but even with that marginal, high marginal rate,

01:03:05.760 --> 01:03:10.520
the effective tax rate that they're very wealthy

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:13.360
were paying was like 40%,

01:03:13.360 --> 01:03:16.440
because of loopholes and so on.

01:03:16.440 --> 01:03:18.320
We need to address that.

01:03:18.320 --> 01:03:20.840
But my question to Nicholas is,

01:03:20.840 --> 01:03:25.840
why should we trust the billionaires

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:30.240
that own these companies to make the right decisions

01:03:30.240 --> 01:03:31.840
about investment?

01:03:31.840 --> 01:03:33.560
Where should it go?

01:03:33.560 --> 01:03:38.000
Why shouldn't that decision be socially determined

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:40.800
rather than by billionaires?

01:03:40.800 --> 01:03:45.800
And I would take a lesson from the movie, Don't Look Up.

01:03:45.800 --> 01:03:49.040
Okay, to me, as a climate scientist,

01:03:49.040 --> 01:03:54.040
that message was that obviously it was about

01:03:54.200 --> 01:03:56.600
the threat of climate catastrophe,

01:03:56.600 --> 01:03:59.120
not really about a asteroid.

01:03:59.120 --> 01:04:01.400
And secondly, the message was,

01:04:01.400 --> 01:04:06.400
if we trust the billionaire solution will be doomed.

01:04:06.600 --> 01:04:08.600
That was, if you watch the movie,

01:04:08.600 --> 01:04:10.240
that's what it ended up.

01:04:10.240 --> 01:04:14.440
And I think that was a very good prescription

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:18.000
about what we should do,

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:22.920
actually, because I believe the world is overpopulated.

01:04:24.120 --> 01:04:26.720
Even one billionaire has won too many.

01:04:26.720 --> 01:04:31.720
I wondered, because just before Nicholas takes a shot at that,

01:04:31.720 --> 01:04:36.720
I mean, the term neoliberal was used earlier.

01:04:38.320 --> 01:04:40.520
And I wondered if anyone wants to offer

01:04:40.520 --> 01:04:43.720
a kind of a definition of what that means.

01:04:43.720 --> 01:04:45.320
And maybe, yeah.

01:04:45.320 --> 01:04:47.560
But what we tell our students is that it needs

01:04:47.560 --> 01:04:50.800
a transition from more public provisioning

01:04:50.800 --> 01:04:53.200
and a public having a mixed economy

01:04:53.200 --> 01:04:55.120
with the government and markets.

01:04:55.120 --> 01:04:58.760
And it means the focus on market liberalization

01:04:58.760 --> 01:05:03.360
and then a transfer also political power from the people,

01:05:03.360 --> 01:05:07.480
from the public, to an entanglement

01:05:07.480 --> 01:05:11.240
between corporate interests and the political interests.

01:05:11.240 --> 01:05:12.440
Now, that's contentious.

01:05:12.440 --> 01:05:15.240
I teach in a department where I'm an economist,

01:05:15.240 --> 01:05:17.480
but my colleagues are human geographers.

01:05:17.480 --> 01:05:27.480
I think what I just said is roughly what they would say.

01:05:27.480 --> 01:05:28.840
If you want me to reply,

01:05:28.840 --> 01:05:31.640
I mean, I don't want to reply about the names.

01:05:31.640 --> 01:05:34.200
I mean, people call names curses all the time.

01:05:34.200 --> 01:05:38.000
I'm not going to get pigeonholed to a particular name.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:39.840
I'm telling you the positions.

01:05:39.840 --> 01:05:42.720
I'm telling you, I'm trying to argue seriously

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:44.920
about what I think needs to be done.

01:05:44.920 --> 01:05:46.640
If you want to argue seriously too,

01:05:46.640 --> 01:05:49.920
you can find a way to talk about the reasons

01:05:49.920 --> 01:05:52.920
why this is not right or this is right.

01:05:52.920 --> 01:05:55.080
It's just saying, oh, we have too many billionaires,

01:05:55.080 --> 01:05:56.360
let's execute them and so on.

01:05:56.360 --> 01:05:58.200
I mean, that's a childist.

01:05:58.200 --> 01:05:59.040
Come on.

01:05:59.040 --> 01:06:03.600
I mean, seriously, I think that there is a serious issue,

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:07.880
very serious, and we have opened at least three or four

01:06:07.880 --> 01:06:10.640
that we need to argue on to talk about them.

01:06:10.640 --> 01:06:13.720
I mean, and I don't think that characterizations

01:06:13.720 --> 01:06:15.800
make any difference, in my opinion.

01:06:15.800 --> 01:06:18.360
I mean, I don't want to talk about it.

01:06:18.360 --> 01:06:20.400
I think it would be useful though,

01:06:20.400 --> 01:06:26.600
to not view proposals to raise the progressivity of the taxes

01:06:26.600 --> 01:06:31.120
somehow a moral indictment of the rich or a statement

01:06:31.120 --> 01:06:33.960
that we're out to get them.

01:06:33.960 --> 01:06:37.800
My effective tax rate, I've learned from my accountant,

01:06:37.800 --> 01:06:40.600
is over 30%.

01:06:40.600 --> 01:06:45.000
Jeff Bezos pays next to nothing in tax.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:47.280
I think when he thinks about investment,

01:06:47.280 --> 01:06:52.320
if he were taxed more heavily, the way we teach investment

01:06:52.320 --> 01:06:56.480
is that if the rate of return on an investment is 6%,

01:06:56.480 --> 01:07:00.600
and you can borrow money at 5%, then you ought to do it.

01:07:00.600 --> 01:07:03.520
You invest if the rate of return is greater

01:07:03.520 --> 01:07:05.000
than your cost of capital.

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:08.280
We don't, in any part of that module, teach them,

01:07:08.280 --> 01:07:11.720
look at your wealth balance and decide whether to invest.

01:07:11.720 --> 01:07:14.840
Maybe that would influence your attitude toward risk.

01:07:14.840 --> 01:07:18.560
But I can't imagine that's going to be a factor for Bezos.

01:07:18.560 --> 01:07:22.240
So taxing his wealth will not change the projects

01:07:22.240 --> 01:07:24.960
he finds it profitable to invest in.

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:28.360
That's not one of the things that's on the table.

01:07:28.360 --> 01:07:30.320
Maybe if he had a little less wealth,

01:07:30.320 --> 01:07:33.560
he wouldn't be as quick to spend money on a rocket ship

01:07:33.560 --> 01:07:35.720
to take a thrill ride into space.

01:07:35.720 --> 01:07:37.440
That's possible.

01:07:37.440 --> 01:07:39.560
It's easier for me to imagine that response

01:07:39.560 --> 01:07:43.200
than that he would back away from an otherwise profitable

01:07:43.200 --> 01:07:44.440
investment.

01:07:44.440 --> 01:07:46.080
But let's go back to the issue.

01:07:46.080 --> 01:07:47.000
What am I saying?

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.400
Why am I saying it he will invest less?

01:07:49.400 --> 01:07:53.880
Because the government will take away this money, OK, for sure.

01:07:53.880 --> 01:07:57.080
And that's the money that are being presently invested

01:07:57.080 --> 01:07:58.320
in whatever way.

01:07:58.320 --> 01:07:59.960
I mean, I'm not even going to argue

01:07:59.960 --> 01:08:02.200
that there are all that there is he's investing them

01:08:02.200 --> 01:08:03.200
in the right way.

01:08:03.200 --> 01:08:04.960
But he's invested somewhere.

01:08:04.960 --> 01:08:08.240
Maybe he's invested in whatever activities Amazon does.

01:08:08.240 --> 01:08:10.400
So this money is invested.

01:08:10.400 --> 01:08:12.480
Now the government is going to take it.

01:08:12.480 --> 01:08:14.320
But the government has mixed incentives.

01:08:14.320 --> 01:08:15.960
I said it before.

01:08:15.960 --> 01:08:21.280
The government has run by politicians

01:08:21.280 --> 01:08:22.440
who want to be reelected.

01:08:22.440 --> 01:08:28.080
And that creates an incentive not to invest whatever 20 billion

01:08:28.080 --> 01:08:29.960
they got from Bezos.

01:08:29.960 --> 01:08:32.760
But to use a significant part of it

01:08:32.760 --> 01:08:36.320
in giving it to the voters, giving it

01:08:36.320 --> 01:08:39.160
to the people who are going to get you reelected.

01:08:39.160 --> 01:08:41.480
Or in your theories, some of you said,

01:08:41.480 --> 01:08:44.200
or giving it to the corporations that will get you reelected.

01:08:44.200 --> 01:08:46.280
You said this, not me, OK?

01:08:46.280 --> 01:08:51.280
But either way, the incentives are not OK anymore.

01:08:51.280 --> 01:08:54.720
The money is taken away from the US economy

01:08:54.720 --> 01:08:57.520
and is given to consumption.

01:08:57.520 --> 01:09:00.440
Or some significant part of it given to consumption.

01:09:00.440 --> 01:09:02.160
And that's about that.

01:09:02.160 --> 01:09:03.800
Now I said that with Build Back Better,

01:09:03.800 --> 01:09:06.000
a lot of the investment is in kids.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:08.160
And it's here, the end gets in schools.

01:09:08.160 --> 01:09:10.280
And those are investments in human capital

01:09:10.280 --> 01:09:14.720
and human capital is a productive asset that we need more on.

01:09:14.720 --> 01:09:17.440
And those are investments that have high returns.

01:09:17.440 --> 01:09:21.320
I mean, we know that they have really high returns.

01:09:21.320 --> 01:09:24.120
The other thing that to bring it back to climate change,

01:09:24.120 --> 01:09:27.520
I think, is to think a little bit about the investments that

01:09:27.520 --> 01:09:31.600
have been made over the last three or four decades

01:09:31.600 --> 01:09:33.160
in renewable energy.

01:09:33.160 --> 01:09:34.920
And one thing that is upsetting to me

01:09:34.920 --> 01:09:38.560
is that the people analyzing what

01:09:38.560 --> 01:09:41.040
this effect has had on the economy and certainly

01:09:41.040 --> 01:09:43.120
on the energy system and on the climate system

01:09:43.120 --> 01:09:46.440
are sociologists, not economists.

01:09:46.440 --> 01:09:50.520
They don't seem to compel to dig into these data.

01:09:50.520 --> 01:09:53.760
But the data show, of course, that it is not

01:09:53.760 --> 01:09:56.680
a one-to-one substitution that, in fact, there

01:09:56.680 --> 01:09:59.360
is more fossil fuel being used.

01:09:59.360 --> 01:10:02.280
This is, in some ways, complementary and not

01:10:02.280 --> 01:10:07.280
a substitute to the existing fossil fuel use, which

01:10:07.280 --> 01:10:11.920
suggests that the economic theory that, oh, you build it,

01:10:11.920 --> 01:10:15.200
they will come, it will substitute whether or not it's,

01:10:15.200 --> 01:10:18.040
and we see this across so many other products too,

01:10:18.040 --> 01:10:21.320
in aquaculture or something else I study,

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:23.480
it's been complementary to capture fisheries.

01:10:23.480 --> 01:10:26.640
It has not been a substitution for it, renewable energy

01:10:26.640 --> 01:10:27.840
and fossil fuels.

01:10:27.840 --> 01:10:30.520
And it's sort of endless, the way in which, again,

01:10:30.520 --> 01:10:33.640
the foundational economic theory has been undermined

01:10:33.640 --> 01:10:35.360
by the empirics.

01:10:35.360 --> 01:10:38.600
But it speaks, again, to this idea of incentives

01:10:38.600 --> 01:10:42.280
versus disincentives and the point I brought up very early

01:10:42.280 --> 01:10:44.800
in the conversation about divestment,

