01:15:11.880 --> 01:15:16.720
been a field called economics, are actually much, much more

01:15:16.720 --> 01:15:19.920
powerful than we even imagined them to be.

01:15:19.920 --> 01:15:21.920
And I think the example that really

01:15:21.920 --> 01:15:26.520
drive that point home for me was the taxes we started

01:15:26.520 --> 01:15:28.920
imposing on smoking.

01:15:28.920 --> 01:15:33.600
We didn't do that really at any significant degree

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:36.720
until we saw studies coming out of Japan

01:15:36.720 --> 01:15:40.200
showing that secondhand smoke exposure caused illnesses

01:15:40.200 --> 01:15:42.400
in others.

01:15:42.400 --> 01:15:45.920
Those lakes are actually fairly weak.

01:15:45.920 --> 01:15:49.560
You don't harm others very much with your secondhand smoke.

01:15:49.560 --> 01:15:51.920
But that was the excuse we felt we needed

01:15:51.920 --> 01:15:54.240
to start discouraging people from smoking.

01:15:54.240 --> 01:15:57.840
We didn't want to say we want to protect you from yourself.

01:15:57.840 --> 01:16:01.280
We want to say it's legitimate to tax you

01:16:01.280 --> 01:16:03.880
because you're harming others.

01:16:03.880 --> 01:16:07.560
It turns out that the real harm you caused others when you

01:16:07.560 --> 01:16:09.480
smoke is not from your secondhand smoke.

01:16:09.480 --> 01:16:13.760
It's by making others in your circle more likely to smoke.

01:16:13.760 --> 01:16:17.560
We take our cues to a much greater degree

01:16:17.560 --> 01:16:21.760
than I think most of us realize by what people around us do.

01:16:21.760 --> 01:16:25.640
I started smoking when I was 14 because most of my friends

01:16:25.640 --> 01:16:26.160
smoked.

01:16:26.160 --> 01:16:28.680
I'm grateful to have quit a few years later.

01:16:28.680 --> 01:16:30.200
Most people don't manage to quit.

01:16:30.200 --> 01:16:32.640
They're stuck for the rest of their lives.

01:16:32.640 --> 01:16:37.400
And a friend who had been a smoker and also a heroin user

01:16:37.400 --> 01:16:41.000
told me that it was much harder for him to quit smoking

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:42.640
than it was for him to quit heroin.

01:16:42.640 --> 01:16:47.200
So perhaps the most addictive substance we know of.

01:16:47.200 --> 01:16:51.120
And the reason the taxes worked, they

01:16:51.120 --> 01:16:52.960
didn't work very well at first.

01:16:52.960 --> 01:16:55.200
If you're a smoker, you're going to keep on smoking.

01:16:55.200 --> 01:16:57.360
You'll just buy less of something else

01:16:57.360 --> 01:17:00.120
when they tax your cigarettes.

01:17:00.120 --> 01:17:02.520
The reason it worked is that some people quit

01:17:02.520 --> 01:17:04.440
and others didn't start.

01:17:04.440 --> 01:17:08.600
Maybe the ones with the least money in the first place

01:17:08.600 --> 01:17:09.480
didn't start.

01:17:09.480 --> 01:17:13.560
That meant each and every peer group had fewer smokers in it.

01:17:13.560 --> 01:17:15.880
That meant everyone else in those groups

01:17:15.880 --> 01:17:19.800
were less likely to start or remain smoking.

01:17:19.800 --> 01:17:22.280
And over time, there's just no other way

01:17:22.280 --> 01:17:24.960
to account for how we went from a smoking rate

01:17:24.960 --> 01:17:29.120
among adults of over half to what it is today, 13%.

01:17:29.120 --> 01:17:30.760
Nobody says, oh, that's horrible.

01:17:30.760 --> 01:17:31.760
We shouldn't have done that.

01:17:31.760 --> 01:17:34.960
Everybody says, thank goodness we took that step.

01:17:34.960 --> 01:17:36.840
And there are steps like that to be

01:17:36.840 --> 01:17:40.080
taken in domain after domain.

01:17:40.080 --> 01:17:41.840
Many of them in the climate.

01:17:41.840 --> 01:17:46.400
We could change energy use patterns in a dramatic way

01:17:46.400 --> 01:17:50.600
just by some gentle shifting of incentives

01:17:50.600 --> 01:17:52.800
and let people influence one another

01:17:52.800 --> 01:17:54.920
to carry the ball the rest of the way home.

